{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538069"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:24:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16125"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.34,0.11,0.17,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104519"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8816"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86846"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4109"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43608"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104519"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic to discuss contraception options. She has been taking the combined oral contraceptive pill but frequently forgets to take it for one to three days at a time. She has recently had a medical termination of pregnancy and is fearful of another unplanned pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history and takes no other regular medications. She works as a professional dancer and desires a contraceptive method that will be more forgiving of missed doses. She specifically requests a method that maintains regular menstrual bleeding while still allowing her to predict and control the timing of her menstrual periods - most importantly being able to delay or skip a period if required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following contraceptive options would best meet this patient\u0027s needs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Depot medroxyprogesterone acetate injection","Vaginal contraceptive ring","Copper intrauterine device","Drospirenone-only pill","Lower dose levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine system"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient requires a contraceptive method that addresses her poor compliance with daily pills while maintaining predictable menstrual cycles and offering cycle control. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evaginal contraceptive ring\u003C/strong\u003E is ideal as it only requires action once monthly, maintains regular withdrawal bleeds, and can be used continuously if cycle manipulation is desired. The NuvaRing is the only vaginal contraceptive ring approved in Australia and releases a combination of ethinylestradiol and etonogestrel. It can be removed for seven days at day 21 of a patient\u0027s cycle and should be replaced on the first day of the next cycle but continues to be effective up to day 28 of a patient\u0027s menstrual cycle if they forget to remove it. The withdrawal bleed time can be shortened to a few days, which may be appropriate for this patient so that she is less likely to forget to insert a new ring. Alternatively, it can be used continuously by replacing the ring every three weeks to skip periods. Additionally, there is no evidence that vigorous exercise causes the vaginal contraceptive ring to dislodge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edepot medroxyprogesterone acetate injection\u003C/strong\u003E requires only twelve-weekly administration but commonly causes irregular bleeding or amenorrhoea. While this would solve the compliance issue, the inability to predict or control bleeding patterns makes this unsuitable for this patient who requires predictable periods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecopper intrauterine device\u003C/strong\u003E provides long-term contraception without hormones but typically causes heavier, longer periods and does not allow for cycle control. This would be problematic for someone who requires predictable periods and the ability to avoid menstruation at specific times.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edrospirenone-only pill\u003C/strong\u003E requires less strict compliance than typical progesterone-only pills, with a 24-hour window period for doses. However, it still requires daily dosing, which would be unsuitable for this patient and would likely lead to contraceptive failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elower dose levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine system\u003C/strong\u003E, while providing excellent long-term contraception and frequently maintaining a regular menstrual cycle, commonly causes irregular spotting in the first few months and has the potential to lead to amenorrhoea. The unpredictable bleeding pattern and inability to manipulate cycles makes this unsuitable for someone requiring precise menstrual control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe vaginal ring is particularly suitable as it provides consistent hormone levels, good cycle control, and flexibility in timing. It can be left in continuously for cycle manipulation when needed, such as during performances. Its monthly administration suits someone who struggles with daily compliance, and its 28-day efficacy window provides forgiveness for late changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The vaginal contraceptive ring provides reliable contraception for women who have difficulty with daily pill compliance.","The vaginal ring can be left in place for up to 28 days and still maintain contraceptive efficacy.","Extended use of the vaginal ring allows for menstrual cycle control, which can be important for lifestyle reasons."],"references":["Wieder D. Examining the efficacy, safety, and patient acceptability of the combined contraceptive vaginal ring (NuvaRing\u00ae). International Journal of Women\u2019s Health. 2010 Nov;401. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2990910/","Family Planning NSW. Vaginal Ring (NuvaRing) [Internet]. Sydney: Family Planning NSW. Available at: https://www.fpnsw.org.au/factsheets/individuals/contraception/vaginal-ring-nuvaring"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86846"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16125"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86846"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T12:50:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T12:51:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8816"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104519"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"}